Under visible irradiation, the PEC behaviors of AChE–GQDs–CuFe2O4 MNCs/mGCE were investigated in 0.1M PBS (pH 7.0) containing 0.7mmolL−1 ATCl before and after incubation with 0.05μgmL−1 chlorpyrifos. As shown in Fig. 5
                        A, the photocurrent of AChE–GQDs–CuFe2O4 MNCs/mGCE in 0.1M PBS (pH 7.0) could be observed obviously (curve a). After incubation with 0.05μgmL−1 chlorpyrifos, the decreased photocurrent was observed at AChE–GQDs–CuFe2O4 MNCs/mGCE (curve b), which was about 1.8 times smaller than that in 0.1M PBS (pH 7.0). Based on this, the PEC sensors in determination of chlorpyrifos were constructed. The possible mechanism for the determination of chlorpyrifos via the PEC based on dual inhibition effect is as follows (Scheme 1
                        ) [50,51]: The good biocompatibility and PEC property of the GQDs–CuFe2O4 MNCs facilitate the immobilization of AChE, which can hydrolyze ATCl into thiocholine and acetate upon irradiation. Thiocholine acts as a sacrificial electron donor to scavenge the holes and improves the efficiency of charge separation, leading to a prominent increase in the photocurrent of the modified enzyme electrode. However, chlorpyrifos, bind to the esterase active site of AChE and thus inhibit its catalytic activity, hindering the production of electron and resulting in the decrease of the photocurrent response (Inhibition II).
